There exist constants $m$ and $n$ so that
\[\overrightarrow{OC} = m \overrightarrow{OA} + n \overrightarrow{OB}.\]Enter the ordered pair $(m,n).$

inference:
Let $\mathbf{a} = \overrightarrow{OA},$ $\mathbf{b} = \overrightarrow{OB},$ and $\mathbf{c} = \overrightarrow{OC}.$  Then we want to find $m$ and $n$ such that
\[\mathbf{c} = m \mathbf{a} + n \mathbf{b}.\]Since $\angle BOC = 45^\circ,$
\[\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = \|\mathbf{b}\| \|\mathbf{c}\| \cos 45^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}.\]Also, $\tan \angle AOC = 7,$ so
\[\frac{\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}\|}{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}} = 7.\]Since $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = \|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{c}\| \cos \angle AOC = \sqrt{2} \cos \angle AOC,$
\[\frac{\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}\|}{\sqrt{2} \cos \angle AOC} = 7.\]Then $\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}\| = 7 \sqrt{2} \cos \angle AOC.$

